# 34_objects_scriptable_smoke — sixth row-bound model Scriptable
# OPENING (s230 m1), modelled on 33_layers_scriptable_smoke
# (renamed from slot 26 in s229 m1) and 27_guides_scriptable_smoke
# (s218 m1).
#
# Validates the design banked in CANON's "Row-bound model Scriptables —
# collection-as-router with transient per-instance proxies" entry,
# applied for the sixth time to the active document's scene-content
# surface. Largest of the row-bound Scriptables — wraps every "real
# scene content" SceneNode (Path / Group / Compound / ClipGroup /
# Blend / Warp / Text / Image / Ref / Measurement) across all layers
# in the active document.
#
# Two addressing surfaces, one router:
#
#   objects         — collection. ONE registry entry. Set queries
#                     (count, all_iids) and invoke-shaped reads
#                     (find_by_name, find_by_type).
#   objects.<iid>   — per-instance proxy. NOT in the registry —
#                     materialised on demand, destroyed at end-of-
#                     statement. Element queries (name, type,
#                     visible, locked, parent_iid, child_count, iid).
#
# The shared `objects` prefix is load-bearing: the router splits a
# dotted token on the first `.`, looks the prefix up in the registry,
# and asks the matched object to resolve the suffix. Collection name
# and proxy prefix MUST be the same string.
#
# ── Why this smoke is mostly trace-inspection ─────────────────────────────
#
# s230 m1 is the OPENING milestone of the multi-session `objects`
# arc. It ships the addressing surface but NO mutating verbs — which
# means the smoke fundamentally can't build up scene objects to
# address (the pattern 33_layers and 27_guides use); `objects new`
# is scheduled m5+ and rides verbs that don't exist yet.
#
# The DSL has only one assertion shape today:
#   assert <object> <property> == <literal>
#
# That shape can't express "the previous line's `result` equals "".
# Negative-side checks (find_by_type "layer" returns ""; objects
# find_by_name "<sentinel>" returns "") therefore get exercised via
# `get` lines and verified by trace inspection — the trace will show
# `= ""` for each one. A human reading the trace confirms the scope-
# boundary contract holds; the smoke's pass/fail/error tally only
# counts the ONE assert at the cross-Scriptable boundary (Phase 4)
# which uses the structurally-valid `assert <object> <property> ==
# <literal>` shape.
#
# Pre-stated count: 1 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#
# Future iteration: when m2+ adds a way to land a known in-scope iid
# (a mutating verb like `objects new`), the proxy round-trip can be
# asserted directly: `assert objects.<bound_var> type == "path"`,
# etc. — same idiom 33_layers and 27_guides use for their proxies.
# The pass count grows; the smoke gains BUILD UP / VALIDATE / TEAR
# DOWN structure.
#
# ── Test isolation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This smoke does NOT mutate the doc via `objects` (no mutating verbs
# in m1). The only mutating step is the `layers new` / `layers
# delete` bracket, which adds an empty test layer (zero scene-object
# children, no objects-scope contribution) and removes it at
# teardown — net document state at end-of-run is identical to start.
# Side effect: two AddLayerCommand entries on the undo stack (same
# chatty-for-undo property the other model Scriptables document).
#
# ── Phases ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#   1. REGISTRY    — list shows `objects` (visual).
#   2. DISPATCH    — count, all_iids dispatch on the active doc
#                    (visual: trace shows = <int>, = <string>).
#   3. SCOPE-NEG   — find_by_type on out-of-scope tokens returns ""
#                    (visual: trace shows = "" repeatedly).
#   4. SCOPE-POS   — cross-Scriptable boundary asserts. Create an
#                    empty test layer via `layers`; `layers
#                    find_by_name` finds it (returns iid). The
#                    bound iid round-trips: `assert layers.<var>
#                    name == "<sentinel>"` PASSES. The
#                    corresponding `objects find_by_name` returns ""
#                    (visual: trace shows = ""). This is the
#                    foundation assert.
#   5. TEARDOWN    — delete the test layer.

#[sub] === Phase 1: REGISTRY ===
#[sub] `objects` should appear in the registry list. We don't assert
#[sub] on the full list (surrounding entries depend on what else is
#[sub] registered); the trace inspection is the check.

list

#[sub] === Phase 2: DISPATCH — collection queries ===
#[sub] count returns an Int; all_iids returns a String. The dispatch
#[sub] working IS the foundation check; the trace shows the values
#[sub] for a human reader to sanity-check that the walk is producing
#[sub] reasonable numbers for whatever doc is open.

get objects count
get objects all_iids

#[sub] === Phase 3: SCOPE-NEG — out-of-scope type tokens return "" ===
#[sub] These dispatches run the doc walk but find no in-scope match.
#[sub] Each line emits `= ""` to the trace. Layer / Guide / special-
#[sub] layer types are out of objects scope (option (ii) from the
#[sub] s230 design fork: real scene contents only). An unknown token
#[sub] also returns "" — the vocabulary is fixed.
#[sub]
#[sub] find_by_type is invoke-shaped (it takes a string arg) — not
#[sub] expressible as `get objects find_by_type "..."` because get
#[sub] expects <object> <property> with no args. The bare invoke
#[sub] form `objects find_by_type "..."` lets the result land in the
#[sub] slot via the `=` emit.

objects find_by_type "layer"
objects find_by_type "guide"
objects find_by_type "guidelayer"
objects find_by_type "reflayer"
objects find_by_type "measurelayer"
objects find_by_type "gridlayer"
objects find_by_type "marginlayer"
objects find_by_type "nonsense_type_token"

#[sub] find_by_name on a sentinel string that almost certainly
#[sub] doesn't match any user-named object returns "". If somehow
#[sub] the user has an object named this exact string, the trace
#[sub] would show its iid instead of "". (Vanishingly unlikely;
#[sub] not a smoke failure path.)

objects find_by_name "__s230_m1_sentinel_no_user_object_uses_this__"

#[sub] === Phase 4: SCOPE-POS — cross-Scriptable boundary assert ===
#[sub] Create an empty test layer. layers.new returns the new
#[sub] layer's iid; bind it to `test_layer`. Rename it to a sentinel
#[sub] so we can find it by name through the `layers` Scriptable.

layers new
set test_layer to result
layers.test_layer rename "objects_smoke_test_layer_s230_m1"

#[sub] `layers find_by_name` for the sentinel returns the test
#[sub] layer's iid (the layers Scriptable owns layer-typed nodes).
#[sub] Bind the result and round-trip it via the proxy — if the
#[sub] find returned the right iid, `layers.<found> name` resolves
#[sub] back to the sentinel. THIS is the smoke's foundation assert.

layers find_by_name "objects_smoke_test_layer_s230_m1"
set found_layer to result
assert layers.found_layer name == "objects_smoke_test_layer_s230_m1"

#[sub] `objects find_by_name` for the SAME sentinel returns ""
#[sub] (layers are out of objects' scope). The trace shows `= ""`;
#[sub] no assert because the result-equals-literal shape isn't
#[sub] expressible in today's DSL. Visual confirmation of the scope
#[sub] partition holding.

objects find_by_name "objects_smoke_test_layer_s230_m1"

#[sub] === Phase 5: TEARDOWN ===
#[sub] Delete the test layer. Doc returns to pre-test structural
#[sub] state. Undo stack carries an AddLayerCommand +
#[sub] DeleteLayerCommand pair.

layers delete test_layer

#[sub] Final registry sanity — list at end, same shape as the
#[sub] start. The `objects` collection is still registered; no
#[sub] `objects.<iid>` entries appear despite the proxies
#[sub] materialised across this run (they're unregistered by
#[sub] construction). Per-instance `objects.<iid>` exercise on
#[sub] valid in-scope iids is DEFERRED to m2+ when a mutating verb
#[sub] exists to land a known iid for the proxy round-trip.

list

#[sub] Done. The s230 m1 foundation surface is validated to the
#[sub] extent the read-side surface allows without any mutating
#[sub] verbs on `objects`:
#[sub]
#[sub]   - `objects` is a registered Scriptable (Phase 1)
#[sub]   - count / all_iids dispatch (Phase 2)
#[sub]   - find_by_type out-of-scope tokens return "" (Phase 3,
#[sub]     visual)
#[sub]   - find_by_name sentinel returns "" (Phase 3, visual)
#[sub]   - cross-Scriptable scope is partitioned: layers find_by_name
#[sub]     finds a layer-named sentinel; objects find_by_name for
#[sub]     the same string returns "" (Phase 4 — one assert + one
#[sub]     visual)
#[sub]
#[sub] Pre-stated: 1 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#[sub]
#[sub] What's NOT covered by m1 (and that's by design):
#[sub]   - Successful per-instance proxy round-trip via an in-scope
#[sub]     iid (needs `objects new` or similar; m5+).
#[sub]   - Mutating verbs (toggle_visible, set_visible, set_locked,
#[sub]     rename, move, reparent, delete, duplicate, new, group,
#[sub]     ungroup). Scheduled m3+ / m4+ / m5+.
#[sub]
#[sub] When m2+ lands proxy-write verbs and a way to mint test
#[sub] objects, this smoke gains BUILD UP / VALIDATE / TEAR DOWN
#[sub] phase structure matching 33_layers / 27_guides.
